   received between January 1, 1998 and December 31, 1998. In addition, on
   January 1, 1998 there were 12 cases pending in mediation, and 13 cases
   which had completed mediation and were in the open period for filing a
   complaint. Of those 83 cases: C 49 cases closed during or after
   mediation -18 cases were settled (including one case that settled after
   District Court suit) -in 28 cases, no further action was taken by the
   covered employee after mediation ended -4 civil actions were filed in
   District Court (one of which was settled); C 13 cases were pending in
   mediation on December 31, 1998; C 10 cases had completed mediation and
   were in the time period when a complaint could be filed; C 12
   complaints were filed after mediation ended. COMPLAINTS If the dispute
   remains unresolved after counseling and mediation, an employee may
   elect to file a civil action in the district courts of the United
   States or to file a complaint with the Office. If a complaint is file
   with the Office, a Hearing Officer is appointed to hear the case and
   issue a decision. Twelve complaints were filed with the Office between
   January 1, 1998 and December 31, 1998 and one complaint was pending on
   January 1, 1998. BASIS OF COMPLAINTS The complaints filed during 1998
   involved the following issues: C alleged discrimination in assignments
   based on race and gender C alleged failure to provide a reasonable
   accommodation for an employee with a disability (2 cases) C alleged
   retaliatory discipline C alleged termination based on age C alleged
   termination based on national origin, race and color C alleged
   discrimination based on race and disability C alleged termination based
   on age and disability C alleged termination based on age and gender C
   alleged failure to promote based on gender C alleged failure to promote
   based on gender and race C alleged harassment and termination based on
   race and in retaliation for opposing practices made unlawful by the CAA
   6 ACTION TAKEN ON COMPLAINTS Any party aggrieved by a Hearing Officer's
   decision may file a petition for review of the decision by the Board of
   Directors of the Office. During January 1, 1998  December 31, 1998:
   HEARINGS C 2 hearing officer decisions were issued; C 6 cases were
   settled or otherwise resolved before the hearings concluded; C 5
   complaints were pending either with hearings scheduled for early 1999
   or awaiting Hearing Officer decisions. APPEALS C No petitions for
   review of Hearing Officer decisions were filed with the Board; 3
   petitions were pending on January 1, 1998; C 2 Hearing Officer
   decisions were not appealed and became the final decisions of the
   Office. BOARD ACTION C 3 Board decisions were issued in 1998; C No
   petitions for review of Hearing Officer decisions were pending on
   December 31, 1998. JUDICIAL REVIEW C 1 Petition for review was filed; C
   One court decision was issued on a petition for review filed in 1997.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit upheld the Board's
   decision. LABOR-MANAGEMENT RELATIONS The Office carries out the Board's
   investigative authorities under section 220 of the CAA, involving
   issues concerning the appropriateness of bargaining units for labor
   organization representation, the duty to bargain, and exceptions to
   arbitrators' awards. During January 1, 1998  December 31, 1998: C 2
   representation petitions were filed; C 1 Board decision was issued
   clarifying that several newly encumbered positions were included in a
   previously certified unit; C 2 Board Decisions and Directions of
   Election were issued, one of which set aside the results of the initial
   election because of objectionable conduct and ordered a second 7
   election (prior to the holding of the second election, the labor
   organization withdrew is representation petition); C 2 election
   agreements were entered into by the parties and approved by the
   Executive Director on behalf of the Board; C 2 elections were
   conducted. As a result of the elections, one labor organization was
   certified as the bargaining representative of employees; C 2 petitions
   were pending on December 31,1998: a representation petition filed by a
   labor organization seeking to represent a unit of approximately 19
   employees, and a unit clarification petition seeking to resolve the
   unit status of certain employees in a bargaining unit certified in
   1997. THE OFFICE OF THE GENERAL COUNSEL The Office of the General
   Counsel is responsible for matters arising under three sections of the
   CAA: section 210  Public Services and Accommodations under the
   Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990; section 215  Occupational
   Safety and Health Act of 1970; and section 220  unfair labor practices
   under chapter 71, of title 5, United States Code. 58 requests for
